.SH "NAME"
Text::VisualWidth::PP \- trimming text by the number of the column s of terminals and mobile phones.
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.Vb 2
\&    use utf8;
\&    use Text::VisualWidth::PP;
\&
\&    Text::VisualWidth::PP::width("XXXXXaiu"); # => 13
\&    Text::VisualWidth::PP::trim("XXXXXaiu", 7); # => "XXX"
\&
\&    # with exporter
\&    use Text::VisualWidth::PP qw(vwidth vtrim);
\&    vwidth("XXXXXaiu"); # => 13
\&    vtrim("XXXXXaiu", 7); # => "XXX"
.Ve
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
This module provides functions to treat half-width and full-width characters and display correct size of text in one line on terminals and mobile phones. You can know the visual width of any text and truncate text by the visual width. Now this module support flagged \s-1UTF\-8\s0 and tested only with Japanese.
.PP
This module is pure perl version of Text::VisualWidth. This is bit slow, but it's not require compiler.
.SH "Ambiguous Characters"
.IX Header "Ambiguous Characters"
This module treats ambiguous characters are half width by default.
.PP
And you can specify the behavior by the \f(CW$Text::VisualWidth::PP::EastAsian\fR flag expressly.
.PP
Note: If \f(CW$Unicode::EastAsianWidth::EastAsian\fR is true on compilation time, this module set \f(CW$Text::VisualWidth::PP::EastAsian\fR as true for backward compatibility.
.PP
If you want to detect the ambw parameter from users' environment, please look Unicode::EastAsianWidth::Detect.
